'''George Theodore Selwyn''' (30 July 1887 – 30 May 1957) was an eminent [[priest]] in the middle part of the 20th century.

He was educated at [[St Lawrence College, Ramsgate]] and [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]].<ref>[[Who's Who|“Who was Who”]]1897-1990 London, [[A & C Black]], 1991 {{ISBN|0-7136-3457-X}}</ref> After a [[Curate|curacy]] at St Matthew’s Church, [[Bayswater]]<ref>[http://www.gowlland.me.uk/images/St_Matthews_Church.jpg, 1910–12 Photo of church]</ref> he emigrated to [[India]] as a [[Church Mission Society|CMS]] [[missionary]], eventually becoming [[Dean (education)|Principal]] of ''St John’s College, [[Palamcottah]]'' and then [[Anglican Bishop of Tinnevelly|Bishop of Tinnevelly]]<ref>''Ecclesiastical News New Bishop of Tinnevelly'' [[The Times]]  Friday, 26 October 1945; pg. 2; Issue 50283; col E</ref> in  1945. He retired in 1953 and died four years later.<ref>''Obituary G. T. Selwyn Church Of South India'' [[The Times]] Friday, 14 June 1957; pg. 13; Issue 53867; col C</ref>
